00:15:33.440 --> 00:15:40.400
 The switch statement evaluates the integer expression in parentheses,

00:15:40.400 --> 00:15:43.480
 in this case, the character c, and compares its value

00:15:43.480 --> 00:15:46.840
 simultaneously to all the cases.

00:15:46.840 --> 00:15:49.400
 Each case must be labeled by an integer or

00:15:49.400 --> 00:15:52.840
 character constant or constant expression.

00:15:52.840 --> 00:15:58.040
 If a case matches the expression value, execution starts at that case.

00:15:58.040 --> 00:16:03.040
 The case labeled default is executed if none of the other cases is satisfied.

00:16:03.040 --> 00:16:04.480
 Default is optional.

00:16:04.480 --> 00:16:10.320
 If it isn't there and none of the cases matches, no action at all takes place.

00:16:10.320 --> 00:16:13.480
 Cases and default can occur in any order.

00:16:13.480 --> 00:16:16.160
 Cases must all be different.

00:16:16.160 --> 00:16:20.480
 The break statement causes an immediate exit from the switch.

00:16:20.480 --> 00:16:25.560
 Because the cases serve as labels, after the code for one case is done,

00:16:25.560 --> 00:16:33.600
 execution falls through to the next, unless you take explicit action to escape.

00:16:33.600 --> 00:16:37.720
 Break and return are the most common ways to leave a switch.

00:16:37.720 --> 00:16:43.200
 A break statement can be used to force an immediate exit from a while, for,

00:16:43.200 --> 00:16:46.760
 and do loops as well, as will be discussed later in this chapter.

00:16:49.600 --> 00:16:52.440
 Falling through the cases is a mixed blessing.

00:16:52.440 --> 00:16:55.480
 On the positive side, it allows multiple cases for

00:16:55.480 --> 00:16:59.080
 a single action, as with blank tab or new line in this example.

00:16:59.080 --> 00:17:00.720
 But it also implies that normally,

00:17:00.720 --> 00:17:04.680
 each case must end with a break to prevent falling through to the next.

00:17:04.680 --> 00:17:08.880
 Falling through from one case to another is not robust,

00:17:08.880 --> 00:17:12.520
 being prone to disintegration when the program is modified.

00:17:12.520 --> 00:17:14.800
 With the exception of multiple labels for

00:17:14.800 --> 00:17:18.760
 a single computation, fall throughs should be used sparingly.

00:17:20.120 --> 00:17:25.360
 As a matter of good form, put a break after the last case, in this case default,

00:17:25.360 --> 00:17:27.560
 although it's logically unnecessary.

00:17:27.560 --> 00:17:30.200
 Someday, when another case gets added at the end,

00:17:30.200 --> 00:17:32.400
 this bit of defensive programming will save you.

00:17:32.400 --> 00:17:38.800
 The switch statement, what is there to say?

00:17:38.800 --> 00:17:43.480
 I think that the switch statement was added to compete with the earlier Fortran

00:17:43.480 --> 00:17:48.400
 computed go to statement, or just to keep low level assembly language programmers

00:17:48.400 --> 00:17:52.480
 from switching into assembly language to implement the concept of a branch table.

00:17:52.480 --> 00:17:56.520
 The authors spend most of the previous section apologizing for

00:17:56.520 --> 00:18:02.160
 the switch statement, so you should perhaps take this as a hint and never use it.

00:18:02.160 --> 00:18:07.480
 There are very few situations where a branch table outperforms a series of this,

00:18:07.480 --> 00:18:12.240
 if then else checks, and those are likely deep in a library or

00:18:12.240 --> 00:18:14.000
 operating system code.

00:18:14.000 --> 00:18:19.200
 Programmers should only use switch if they understand what a branch table is,

00:18:19.200 --> 00:18:21.760
 and why a branch table is more efficient for

00:18:21.760 --> 00:18:24.560
 the particular bit of a program they're writing.

00:18:24.560 --> 00:18:29.880
 Otherwise, just use else if and do the readers of your code a favor.

00:18:29.880 --> 00:18:36.320
 3.5 loops, while and for.

00:18:36.320 --> 00:18:40.120
 We have already countered the while and for loops.

00:18:40.120 --> 00:18:45.880
 In while statement, the expression is evaluated.

00:18:45.880 --> 00:18:50.760
 If it is non-zero, the statement is executed and the expression is re-evaluated.

00:18:50.760 --> 00:18:54.160
 This cycle continues until the expression becomes a zero,

00:18:54.160 --> 00:18:58.280
 at which point execution resumes after the statement.

00:18:58.280 --> 00:19:05.360
 The for statement, for, expression one semicolon, expression two semicolon,

00:19:05.360 --> 00:19:10.520
 expression three, close parenthesis, statement is equivalent to expression one

00:19:10.520 --> 00:19:15.040
 semicolon, while, open parenthesis, expression two, closed parenthesis,

00:19:15.040 --> 00:19:21.480
 open curly brace, statement, expression three semicolon, closed curly brace.

00:19:21.480 --> 00:19:27.080
 Grammatically, the three components of the four are expressions.

00:19:27.080 --> 00:19:30.360
 Most commonly, expression one and expression three are assignments or

00:19:30.360 --> 00:19:34.600
 function calls, and expression two is a relational expression.

00:19:34.600 --> 00:19:38.440
 Any of the three parts can be omitted, although the semicolons must remain.

00:19:38.440 --> 00:19:42.800
 If expression one or expression three is left out,

00:19:42.800 --> 00:19:47.080
 it is simply dropped from the expansion.

00:19:47.080 --> 00:19:51.200
 If the test expression two is not present, it is taken as permanently true.

00:19:51.200 --> 00:19:56.920
 So the code for open parenthesis, semicolon, semicolon, closed parenthesis,

00:19:56.920 --> 00:20:01.760
 open curly brace, dot, dot, dot, closed curly brace is an infinite loop.

00:20:01.760 --> 00:20:05.960
 Presumably to be broken by some other means such as a break or a return.

00:20:05.960 --> 00:20:11.680
 Whether to use while or for is largely a matter of taste.

00:20:11.680 --> 00:20:17.200
 For example, in the code, while, open parenthesis, open parenthesis, c equals

00:20:17.200 --> 00:20:23.080
 get char, open parenthesis, closed parenthesis, equal, equal, quote, space, quote.

00:20:23.080 --> 00:20:27.440
 Or c equal equal, quote, backslash, end quote.

00:20:27.440 --> 00:20:33.960
 Or c equal equal, quote, backslash, t quote, close parenthesis, semicolon.

00:20:33.960 --> 00:20:37.680
 Skipping white characters, there is no initialization or

00:20:37.680 --> 00:20:40.360
 reinitialization, so while seems more natural.

00:20:40.360 --> 00:20:45.960
 The for is clearly superior when there is simple initialization and

00:20:45.960 --> 00:20:50.400
 reinitialization, since it keeps the loop control statements close together and

00:20:50.400 --> 00:20:52.360
 visible at the top of the loop.

00:20:52.360 --> 00:20:58.600
 This is the most obvious in for open parenthesis i equals 0 semicolon i less

00:20:58.600 --> 00:21:04.440
 than n semicolon i plus plus closed parenthesis, which is the c idiom for

00:21:04.440 --> 00:21:07.720
 processing the first n elements of an array.

00:21:07.720 --> 00:21:11.680
 The analog of a Fortran or PL1 do loop.

00:21:11.680 --> 00:21:15.440
 The analogy is not perfect, however, since the limits of a for loop can be

00:21:15.440 --> 00:21:19.280
 altered within the loop and the controlling variable i retains its value

00:21:19.280 --> 00:21:22.440
 when the loop terminates for any reason.

00:21:22.440 --> 00:21:25.640
 Because the components of the for are arbitrary expressions,

00:21:25.640 --> 00:21:30.240
 for loops are not restricted to arithmetic progressions.

00:21:30.240 --> 00:21:35.480
 Nonetheless, it is bad style to force unrelated computations into a for.

00:21:35.480 --> 00:21:38.800
 It is best reserved for loop control operations.

