00:26:12.800 --> 00:26:17.800
 Just a swap of v and v sub j plus gap, v sub j and v sub j plus gap.

00:26:17.800 --> 00:26:23.320
 Close curly brace, and that closed the innermost for loop, and

00:26:23.320 --> 00:26:27.760
 then the next close curly brace closes the function.

00:26:27.760 --> 00:26:29.680
 There are three nested loops.

00:26:29.680 --> 00:26:32.600
 The outermost loop controls the gap between the compared elements,

00:26:32.600 --> 00:26:37.840
 shrinking it from n over two by a factor of two each pass until it becomes zero.

00:26:37.840 --> 00:26:41.720
 The middle loop compares each pair of elements that is separated by gap.

00:26:41.720 --> 00:26:45.560
 The innermost loop reverses any elements that are out of order.

00:26:45.560 --> 00:26:49.520
 Since gap is eventually reduced to one, all elements are eventually ordered

00:26:49.520 --> 00:26:50.880
 correctly.

00:26:50.880 --> 00:26:55.200
 Note that the generality of the form makes the outer loop fit the same form as

00:26:55.200 --> 00:26:59.040
 the others, even though it is not an arithmetic progression.

00:26:59.040 --> 00:27:09.880
 One final C operator is the comma, which most often finds use in the for statement.

00:27:09.880 --> 00:27:14.360
 A pair of expressions separated by a comma is evaluated left to right, and

00:27:14.360 --> 00:27:19.840
 the type and value of the result are the type and value of the right operand.

00:27:19.840 --> 00:27:21.120
 Thus, in a for statement,

00:27:21.120 --> 00:27:25.560
 it is possible to place multiple expressions in the various parts.

00:27:25.560 --> 00:27:29.320
 For example, to process two parallel indices.

00:27:29.320 --> 00:27:31.520
 This is illustrated in the function reverse,

00:27:31.520 --> 00:27:35.120
 which reverses the function string in place.

