00:36:09.000 --> 00:36:10.960
 3.8 continue.

00:36:10.960 --> 00:36:16.280
 The continue statement is related to break, but less often used.

00:36:16.280 --> 00:36:21.160
 It causes the next iteration of the enclosing loop, for, while, or do, to begin.

00:36:21.160 --> 00:36:25.480
 In the while and do, this means that the test part is executed immediately.

00:36:25.480 --> 00:36:28.600
 In the for, control passes to the reinitialization step.

00:36:28.600 --> 00:36:33.840
 Control, by the way, continue applies only to loops, not to switch.

00:36:33.840 --> 00:36:38.640
 A continue inside a switch statement inside of a loop causes the next loop iteration.

00:36:39.640 --> 00:36:45.320
 As an example, this fragment processes only positive elements in the array a.

00:36:45.320 --> 00:36:46.480
 Negative values are skipped.

00:36:46.480 --> 00:36:53.400
 For, open paren, i equals zero, semicolon, i less than n, semicolon,

00:36:53.400 --> 00:36:57.320
 i plus plus, close paren, open curly brace.

00:36:57.320 --> 00:37:02.240
 If, open paren, a sub i less than zero, close paren, continue.

00:37:02.240 --> 00:37:07.560
 This line skips the negative elements, and then the rest of the body of the loop,

00:37:07.560 --> 00:37:12.000
 dot dot dot, is, will run only for the positive elements of the loop.

00:37:12.000 --> 00:37:14.080
 And the loop finishes with a close curly brace.

00:37:14.080 --> 00:37:20.720
 The continue statement is often used when part of the loop that follows is complicated,

00:37:20.720 --> 00:37:25.200
 so that reversing a test and indenting another level would nest the program too deeply.

00:37:25.200 --> 00:37:28.440
 It's time for a bit of an aside.

00:37:28.440 --> 00:37:33.560
 Now that we have seen the break and continue language structures in C,

00:37:33.560 --> 00:37:37.680
 that also have made it into C-like languages, and learned about middle tested loops,

00:37:37.680 --> 00:37:41.120
 it is time to revisit the structured programming debate.

00:37:41.120 --> 00:37:44.960
 And the need for priming operations when a program must process all data until

00:37:44.960 --> 00:37:48.880
 it finishes and still handle the there is no data at all situation.

00:37:48.880 --> 00:37:53.640
 In the previous chapter, the author somewhat skirted the issue by using a top

00:37:53.640 --> 00:37:57.960
 tested while loop and a side effect statement with residual value that was

00:37:57.960 --> 00:38:00.440
 compared to EOF to decide when to exit the loop.

