00:38:42.440 --> 00:38:48.280
 Now you will almost never see a read all characters until EOF written this way

00:38:48.280 --> 00:38:55.720
 because it is not the way KNR told us to reuse a while loop for this.

00:38:55.720 --> 00:39:01.000
 But the for loop formulation is probably clearer than the while formulation,

00:39:01.000 --> 00:39:05.440
 especially to a reader who's not familiar with the assignment side effect idiom,

00:39:05.440 --> 00:39:07.040
 commonly used in C.

00:39:07.040 --> 00:39:12.400
 In particular, the for formulation does not require that the assignment statement

00:39:12.400 --> 00:39:15.160
 has a residual value of the value that was assigned.

00:39:16.280 --> 00:39:18.240
 The first part of the for is a priming read.

00:39:18.240 --> 00:39:22.840
 The second part of the for is a top text tested exit criteria that works both for

00:39:22.840 --> 00:39:26.240
 no data and after all data has been read and processed.

00:39:26.240 --> 00:39:29.640
 And the third part of the for is done at the bottom of the loop to advance to

00:39:29.640 --> 00:39:34.000
 the next character or encounter EOF before going back to the top and

00:39:34.000 --> 00:39:35.440
 doing the loop test.

00:39:35.440 --> 00:39:41.120
 The call to get char is done twice in the for formulation of the read all available

00:39:41.120 --> 00:39:42.160
 data loop.

00:39:42.160 --> 00:39:46.040
 And while we don't like to repeat ourselves in code, if it is a small and

00:39:46.040 --> 00:39:50.600
 obvious bit of code, perhaps this code is more clear with a bit of repetition.

00:39:50.600 --> 00:39:57.880
 So, with all this as background, you can take this page of the document and

00:39:57.880 --> 00:40:02.440
 sit down with a friend at a coffee shop and debate as long as you like about

00:40:02.440 --> 00:40:05.280
 which is the better formulation for the read all available data.

00:40:05.280 --> 00:40:11.120
 But if at that coffee shop you ask Dr. Chuck's opinion, neither of these is ideal

00:40:11.120 --> 00:40:15.000
 because in the real world we build data oriented loops that usually do a lot more

00:40:15.000 --> 00:40:17.080
 than get one character from standard input.

00:40:17.080 --> 00:40:23.120
 My formulation of a data loop will upset the structured programming purists and

00:40:23.120 --> 00:40:26.200
 probably upset Kernigan and Ritchie as well.

00:40:26.200 --> 00:40:29.400
 But I write code in the real world, so here is my version.

00:40:29.400 --> 00:40:34.080
