00:43:48.680 --> 00:43:54.600
 semi-colon, i less than n, semi-colon, i plus plus, close parenthesis.

00:43:54.600 --> 00:43:59.840
 For, open parenthesis, j equals zero, semi-colon, j less than m,

00:43:59.840 --> 00:44:03.080
 semi-colon, j plus plus, close parenthesis.

00:44:03.080 --> 00:44:08.040
 If, open parenthesis, v sub i sub j less than zero, close parenthesis,

00:44:08.040 --> 00:44:13.160
 go to, found, otherwise, and then you handle and you keep going.

00:44:13.160 --> 00:44:19.480
 And then found, colon, include, is where it comes to, jumps to.

00:44:19.480 --> 00:44:24.280
 Code involving a go to can always be written without one, but though perhaps

00:44:24.280 --> 00:44:27.160
 at the price of somewhat repeated tests or an extra variable.

00:44:27.160 --> 00:44:32.040
 For example, the array search becomes, found equals zero.

00:44:33.120 --> 00:44:38.120
 For, open parenthesis, i equals zero, semi-colon, i less than n,

00:44:38.120 --> 00:44:43.080
 ampersand ampersand, exclamation, found, semi-colon, i plus plus.

00:44:43.080 --> 00:44:47.640
 For, open parenthesis, j equals zero, semi-colon, j less than m,

00:44:47.640 --> 00:44:53.160
 ampersand ampersand, exclamation, found, semi-colon, j plus plus.

00:44:53.160 --> 00:44:57.080
 Found equals v sub i sub j less than zero.

00:44:57.080 --> 00:45:01.400
 If found, continue, else not found.

00:45:01.400 --> 00:45:03.840
 Although we are not dogmatic about the matter,

00:45:03.840 --> 00:45:08.920
 it does seem that go to statements should be used sparingly, if at all.

00:45:08.920 --> 00:45:14.880
 I would add, before we leave control flow, I need to say that I agree with

00:45:14.880 --> 00:45:17.280
 structure programming experts, as well as Kernigan and

00:45:17.280 --> 00:45:20.200
 Ritchie, in that the go to is universally a bad idea.

00:45:20.200 --> 00:45:25.120
 There are a lot of little details that make them a real problem.

00:45:25.120 --> 00:45:28.800
 Things like how the stack works in function calls, and how code blocks

00:45:28.800 --> 00:45:31.920
 happen, and patching the stack up correctly when a go to happens

00:45:31.920 --> 00:45:33.720
 in the middle of a deeply nested mess.

00:45:33.720 --> 00:45:38.720
 You might be tempted to use a go to when you want to exit multiple

00:45:38.720 --> 00:45:40.600
 nested loops in a single statement.

00:45:40.600 --> 00:45:43.400
 Break and continue only exit the innermost loop.

00:45:43.400 --> 00:45:45.760
 The authors use this example above, but

00:45:45.760 --> 00:45:48.720
 are quite lukewarm when describing it as a use of go to.

00:45:48.720 --> 00:45:54.920
 Usually, if your problem is that complex, putting things in a function and

00:45:54.920 --> 00:45:58.840
 using return, or adding a few if statements is a better choice.

00:45:58.840 --> 00:46:01.640
 The Dr. Chuck middle-tested loop, data processing,

00:46:01.640 --> 00:46:04.520
 solves this because the loop is always the innermost loop.

00:46:04.520 --> 00:46:10.400
 Also, as new languages were built, the concept of exceptions became part of

00:46:10.400 --> 00:46:15.000
 language design, and was a by far more elegant solution,

00:46:15.000 --> 00:46:18.920
 to a path of some deeply nested code that just needs to get out.

00:46:18.920 --> 00:46:22.360
 So most of the time, you think the go to might be a good idea,

00:46:22.360 --> 00:46:27.400
 you should lean towards a throw-catch pattern to make your intention clear.

00:46:27.400 --> 00:46:30.560
 It is one of the reasons why we prefer languages like Java or

00:46:30.560 --> 00:46:33.600
 Python over C when writing general purpose code.

00:46:33.600 --> 00:46:43.680
 This work is based on the 1978 C Programming book written by Brian W.

00:46:43.680 --> 00:46:44.880
 Kernighan and Dennis M.

00:46:44.880 --> 00:46:45.960
 Ritchie.

00:46:45.960 --> 00:46:50.720
 Their book is copyright all rights reserved by AT&T, but is used in this

00:46:50.720 --> 00:46:56.020
 work under fair use because of the book's historical and scholarly significance.

00:46:56.020 --> 00:47:00.360
 It's lack of availability and the lack of an accessible version of the book.

00:47:00.360 --> 00:47:03.760
 The book is augmented in places to help understand its right place in

00:47:03.760 --> 00:47:08.000
 a historical context amidst the major changes of the 1970s and

00:47:08.000 --> 00:47:13.360
 1980s as computer science evolved from a hardware-first vendor-centered approach

00:47:13.360 --> 00:47:16.640
 to a software-centered approach where portable operating systems and

00:47:16.640 --> 00:47:19.640
 applications written in C could run on any hardware.

00:47:21.120 --> 00:47:25.520
 This is not the ideal book to learn C Programming because the 1978 edition

00:47:25.520 --> 00:47:28.240
 does not reflect the modern C language.

00:47:28.240 --> 00:47:32.760
 Using an obsolete book gives us an opportunity to take students back in time

00:47:32.760 --> 00:47:37.320
 and understand how the C language was evolving as it laid the groundwork for

00:47:37.320 --> 00:47:39.480
 a future with portable applications.

